##Key concepts:

Command and control: WHen malware infects a machine, it needs to talk with the hackers instead of using a hardcoded IP address which will be blocked, the malware 
makes a DNS request for a domain owned by the hacker.

DNS tunneling: Attackers can sneak stolen data out of a highly secure company by hiding chunks of data inside DNS query packets, because firewalls almost always
allow DNS traffic out, this data goes completely unnoticed

##Tools:
Dig/nslookup: command-line utilities used to query DNS servers and look up specific resource records.
Sublist3r/amass: Tools used to search for hidden subdomains during the investigation phase.

##Blue team:
Process: Look for unusual DNS activity, if a computer makes thousands of rapid requests for strange domains like x1a9f.attacker.com, they recognize it as DNS tunneling
or malware c2. They also use passive DNS logs to trace histories of where domains have pointed over time.

End goal: To detect compromised internal systems and block traffic to dangerous domains.

##Red team:
Process: Use DNS reconnaissance to map out a company's infrastructure. By querying MX records, they find out who handles the company's email. By querying
TXT or A records, they find exposed development servers. Configure malware to use DGA(Domain Generation Algorithms) to generate hundreds of random domains a day for
C2, staying ahead of defender blocklists.

End goal: To find hidden infrastructure targets targets or establish unblockable communication channels with infected hosts. 

